{"insight":"No mirror is neutral when it bends","publicTitle":"The Bent Mirror of Self","plainSummary":"A theory that treats the self as made cannot fairly settle whether the self is made.","atAGlance":"When a theory begins by treating the self as something made, it has already chosen a side. It can help us examine how the brain speaks of selfhood. It cannot fairly settle whether awareness is deeper than thought. The test is whether it can honor both views without changing one into the other.","keyPoints":["A hidden starting point can decide the answer before inquiry begins.","The danger is mistaking translation for proof.","Test whether both sides remain intact after being restated."],"match":["already took a side"],"tags":["self","awareness","brain","inquiry"]}
